Compensation as of Fiscal Year 2017. 

HotApp International, Inc. Key Developments

HotApp International, Inc. Announces Executive Changes
Jun 22 17
On June 21, 2017, Chan Heng Fai voluntarily resigned as Chief Executive Officer and President of HotApp International Inc. Mr. Chan will remain as Chairman of the company’s Board of Directors. On June 21, 2017, the company appointed Lum Kan Fai as the company’s CEO and President. Mr. Lum, age 54, has served as a member of the company’s Board of Directors and as the company’s Chief Technology Officer, since June 14, 2015. In connection with Mr. Lum’s appointment as the company’s CEO and President, Mr. Lum has voluntarily resigned his position as the company’s CTO. Prior to his appointment to the company’s Board of Directors and his position as the company’s CTO, Mr. Lum has had over 30 years of technology business experience in multinational corporations. Currently, Mr. Lum also serves on the Board of Directors of Applecraft Asia Ltd.


Hotapp International Inc. Reports Unaudited Consolidated Earnings Results for the First Quarter Ended March 31, 2017
May 16 17
Hotapp International Inc. reported unaudited consolidated earnings results for the first quarter ended March 31, 2017. For the quarter, the company reported revenues of $66,178. Loss from operations was $199,390 compared to $333,785 a year ago. Loss before taxes was $133,818 compared to $333,031 a year ago. Net loss applicable to common shareholders was $133,818 or $0.02 per basic and diluted share compared to $340,068 or $0.06 per basic and diluted share a year ago. Net cash used in operating activities was $292,608 compared to $403,532 a year ago. Acquisition of fixed asset was $3,898 compared to $2,515 a year ago.


Hotapp International Inc. Auditor Raises 'Going Concern' Doubt
Apr 14 17
Hotapp International Inc. filed its 10-K on Apr 14, 2017 for the period ending Dec 31, 2016. In this report its auditor, Rosenberg Rich Baker Berman & Company, gave an unqualified opinion expressing doubt that the company can continue as a going concern.


